====Homophones====
*[[meat]], [[meet]]

===Etymology 1===
From Old French ''[[#Old French|mete]]'', from Latin ''[[meta#Latin|mēta]]'' "post, goal, marker".

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[boundary]] or other limit; a boundary-marker.

===Etymology 2===
Old English ''[[metan]]'', from Germanic ''*meta-'', from Indo-European ''*med-'' ‘measure, consider’.  Cognate with Dutch ''[[meten]]'', German ''[[messen]]'', Swedish ''[[mäta]]''; and (from Indo-European) with Greek ''[[μέδεσθαι]]'' ‘care for’, Latin ''[[metiri|mētīrī]]'' ‘to measure’.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|met|es}}

# {{italbrac|transitive|poetic}} To [[measure]].
#:*'''1611''': For with what judgment ye judge, ye shall be judged: and with what measure ye '''mete''', it shall be measured to you again. (''King James Version'', Matthew 7:2)
# {{italbrac|transitive|usually with “out”}} To [[dispense]], [[measure]] (out), [[allot]] (especially [[punishment]], reward etc.).

